{"title_page": "439", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|439}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Year nav|439}}\n{{M1 year in topic}}\n[[File:Licinia Eudoxia.JPG|thumb|Empress [[Licinia Eudoxia]]]]\n__NOTOC__\nYear '''439''' ('''[[Roman numerals|CDXXXIX]]''') was a [[common year starting on Sunday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]]. At the time, it was known as the '''Year of the Consulship of Theodosius and Festus''' (or, less frequently, '''year 1192 ''[[Ab urbe condita]]'''''). The denomination 439 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the [[Anno Domini]] [[calendar era]] became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n\n=== By place ===\n\n==== Europe ====\n\n===== Britain =====\n* [[Battle of Guoloph]]: Vitalinus (possibly [[Vortigern]]) is defeated at the hands of [[Ambrosius Aurelianus]] and a combined force of Romano-British forces from across southern Britain.\n\n===== Roman Empire =====\n* [[Litorius]], Roman general (''[[Magister militum#per Gallias|Magister militum per Gallias]]''), lays siege to [[Toulouse]]. During the decisive battle before the [[Defensive wall|walls]] he suffers a severe defeat and is killed, and only the heavy loss of [[Visigoths]] makes King [[Theodoric I]] decide to agree to a provisional restoration of the ''[[status quo]]''.\n* [[Licinia Eudoxia]], wife of emperor [[Valentinian III]], is granted the title of [[Augusta (honorific)|''Augusta'']] following the birth of their daughter [[Princess Eudocia|Eudocia]].\n* [[Greek language|Greek]] becomes an official language in the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman Empire]].\n\n==== Balkans ====\n* Winter &ndash; [[Huns|Hun]] and [[Roman Empire|Roman]] envoys meet at [[Ora\u0161je, Bosnia|Margum]] (modern [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]), an important [[Market (place)|market]] town on the [[Sava|Sava River]]. After negotiations, [[Attila]] and his brother [[Bleda]], who are present, accept a four-point peace plan. [[Trade|Trading]] rights between the two states are confirmed and emperor [[Theodosius II]] pays an annual [[tribute]] of 700 pounds of [[gold]].<ref>The End of Empire (p. 117). Christopher Kelly, 2009. {{ISBN|978-0-393-33849-2}}</ref>\n\n==== Africa ====\n\n* King [[Genseric]] breaks his treaty with the [[Western Roman Empire]] and invades [[Africa (Roman province)|Africa Proconsularis]].\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; [[Carthage]] [[Battle of Carthage (439)|falls]] to the [[Vandals]]. Genseric makes it his capital and establishes the [[Vandals|Vandal Kingdom]].\n* The Vandals establish a North African [[granary]] that enables them to enforce their will on other nations, who are dependent on [[North Africa]] for [[Cereal|grain]] and other [[Staple food|food staples]].\n* Winter &ndash; The Vandals conquer [[Sicily]], [[Sardinia]], [[Corsica]] and the [[Balearic Islands]].\n\n====Scotland====\n* A hardened tribe of elite warriors assumed this title after an 8 hour long battle against a fascist government outfit. They lost the fight but they won the war against a communist regime who enforced a strict \"no partying\" rule that was really gay and that no-one liked. RIP to this band of brothers.\n\n=== By topic ===\n\n==== Religion ====\n* [[Isaac of Armenia|Isaac the Great]], Armenian apostolic [[patriarch]], dies at Ashtishat. He helped to develop a Greek-inspired [[alphabet]], and translate the [[Bible]], along with various Christian writings, into [[Armenian alphabet|Armenian]].\n* The [[monastery]] of [[Mar Saba]] is founded near [[Bethlehem]] ([[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]).\n</onlyinclude>\n\n== Births ==\n* [[Princess Eudocia|Eudocia]], [[Vandals|Vandal]] queen and daughter of [[Valentinian III]]\n* [[Emperor Ming of Liu Song|Ming Di]], emperor of the [[Liu Song Dynasty]] (d. [[472]])\n* [[Sabbas the Sanctified]], Christian [[monk]] and [[saint]] (d. [[532]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[Isaac of Armenia|Isaac]], [[List of Catholicoi of Armenia|patriarch of Armenia]] (b. [[338]])\n* [[Litorius]], general of the [[Western Roman Empire]]\n* [[Empress Sima Maoying|Sima Maoying]], empress of the Liu Song Dynasty (b. [[393]])   \n* [[Spearthrower Owl]], ruler of [[Teotihuacan]] ([[Valley of Mexico|Mexico]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:439}}\n[[Category:439| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|439}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Year nav|439}}\n{{M1 year in topic}}\n[[File:Licinia Eudoxia.JPG|thumb|Empress [[Licinia Eudoxia]]]]\n__NOTOC__\nYear '''439''' ('''[[Roman numerals|CDXXXIX]]''') was a [[common year starting on Sunday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]]. At the time, it was known as the '''Year of the Consulship of Theodosius and Festus''' (or, less frequently, '''year 1192 ''[[Ab urbe condita]]'''''). The denomination 439 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the [[Anno Domini]] [[calendar era]] became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n\n=== By place ===\n\n==== Europe ====\n\n===== Britain =====\n* [[Battle of Guoloph]]: Vitalinus (possibly [[Vortigern]]) is defeated at the hands of [[Ambrosius Aurelianus]] and a combined force of Romano-British forces from across southern Britain.\n\n===== Roman Empire =====\n* [[Litorius]], Roman general (''[[Magister militum#per Gallias|Magister militum per Gallias]]''), lays siege to [[Toulouse]]. During the decisive battle before the [[Defensive wall|walls]] he suffers a severe defeat and is killed, and only the heavy loss of [[Visigoths]] makes King [[Theodoric I]] decide to agree to a provisional restoration of the ''[[status quo]]''.\n* [[Licinia Eudoxia]], wife of emperor [[Valentinian III]], is granted the title of [[Augusta (honorific)|''Augusta'']] following the birth of their daughter [[Princess Eudocia|Eudocia]].\n* [[Greek language|Greek]] becomes an official language in the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman Empire]].\n\n==== Balkans ====\n* Winter &ndash; [[Huns|Hun]] and [[Roman Empire|Roman]] envoys meet at [[Ora\u0161je, Bosnia|Margum]] (modern [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]), an important [[Market (place)|market]] town on the [[Sava|Sava River]]. After negotiations, [[Attila]] and his brother [[Bleda]], who are present, accept a four-point peace plan. [[Trade|Trading]] rights between the two states are confirmed and emperor [[Theodosius II]] pays an annual [[tribute]] of 700 pounds of [[gold]].<ref>The End of Empire (p. 117). Christopher Kelly, 2009. {{ISBN|978-0-393-33849-2}}</ref>\n\n==== Africa ====\n\n* King [[Genseric]] breaks his treaty with the [[Western Roman Empire]] and invades [[Africa (Roman province)|Africa Proconsularis]].\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; [[Carthage]] [[Battle of Carthage (439)|falls]] to the [[Vandals]]. Genseric makes it his capital and establishes the [[Vandals|Vandal Kingdom]].\n* The Vandals establish a North African [[granary]] that enables them to enforce their will on other nations, who are dependent on [[North Africa]] for [[Cereal|grain]] and other [[Staple food|food staples]].\n* Winter &ndash; The Vandals conquer [[Sicily]], [[Sardinia]], [[Corsica]] and the [[Balearic Islands]].\n\n====Scotland====\nA hardened tribe of elite warriors assumed this title after an 8 hour long battle against a fascist government outfit. They lost the fight but they won the war against a communist regime who enforced a strict \"no partying\" rule that was really gay and that no-one liked. RIP to this band of brothers.\n\n=== By topic ===\n\n==== Religion ====\n* [[Isaac of Armenia|Isaac the Great]], Armenian apostolic [[patriarch]], dies at Ashtishat. He helped to develop a Greek-inspired [[alphabet]], and translate the [[Bible]], along with various Christian writings, into [[Armenian alphabet|Armenian]].\n* The [[monastery]] of [[Mar Saba]] is founded near [[Bethlehem]] ([[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]).\n</onlyinclude>\n\n== Births ==\n* [[Princess Eudocia|Eudocia]], [[Vandals|Vandal]] queen and daughter of [[Valentinian III]]\n* [[Emperor Ming of Liu Song|Ming Di]], emperor of the [[Liu Song Dynasty]] (d. [[472]])\n* [[Sabbas the Sanctified]], Christian [[monk]] and [[saint]] (d. [[532]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[Isaac of Armenia|Isaac]], [[List of Catholicoi of Armenia|patriarch of Armenia]] (b. [[338]])\n* [[Litorius]], general of the [[Western Roman Empire]]\n* [[Empress Sima Maoying|Sima Maoying]], empress of the Liu Song Dynasty (b. [[393]])   \n* [[Spearthrower Owl]], ruler of [[Teotihuacan]] ([[Valley of Mexico|Mexico]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:439}}\n[[Category:439| ]]\n", "name_user": "Geckooverdrive666", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eScotland", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/439"}
{"title_page": "Sian Evans", "text_new": "{{for|the author|Si\u00e2n Evans}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Sian Evans\n| image            = Kosheen Sian Evans Wien2008.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = In Vienna, 2008\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Sian Evans\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1971|10|09}}\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Caerphilly]], Wales\n| instrument       = \n| genre            = [[Trip hop]], [[drum and bass]], rock, [[synthpop]], [[Breakbeat]], [[Dubstep]], [[Electro (music)|Electro]], [[Trance music|Trance]]\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter\n| years_active     = 1997\u2013present\n| label            = [[Ministry of Sound]], [[Moksha Records]], [[Universal Music Group]], [[Sony BMG Music Entertainment]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Kosheen]], [[DJ Fresh]], [[Roger Shah]], [[Jody Wisternoff]], [[Dino Psaras]], [[Chicane (musician)|Chicane]], Dr. Meaker, Jolyon Petch, Brains, Martin Eyerer, Paul Hazendonk, Bent, Lee Dagger\n| website          = [http://sian-evans.com www.sian-evans.com]\n}}\n\n'''Sian Evans''' (born 9 October 1971) is a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] singer.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/sian-evans-celebrates-no1-hit-1820711 | work = [[Wales Online]] | title = Sian Evans celebrates No.1 hit with DJ Fresh}}</ref> Throughout the 2000s, she was [[front woman]] and singer-songwriter of the band [[Kosheen]], a [[Trip hop|trip-hop]]/[[drum & bass]] group that, during that decade, placed two albums within the Top Ten of the [[UK Albums Chart]]. She has also joined a list of Welsh artists to have topped the [[UK singles chart]] with collaboration on the track '[[Louder (DJ Fresh song)|Louder]]' with [[DJ Fresh]]. Kosheen disbanded in 2016.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums with Kosheen===\n\n{| c