es Foley |title= The Memoirs of General Grivas |year= 1964 |publisher= Longmans |location= London |isbn= }}\n*{{cite book|author=Makarios (Kypros, Archiepiskopos, III.)|title=Hapanta Archiepiskopou Kyprou Makariou 3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gi7SrQEACAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Hidryma Archiepiskopou Makariou 3.|isbn=978-9963-556-44-1}}\n\n;Secondary sources\n*{{cite book|last1=Fole\u00ff|first1=Charles |last2=Scobie|first2=W. I. |title=The struggle for Cyprus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H9FmAAAAMAAJ|year=1975|publisher=Hoover Institution Press|isbn=978-0-8179-1371-7}}\n\n{{Megali Idea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eoka}}\n[[Category:Cyprus dispute]]\n[[Category:Greek Cypriot nationalism]]\n[[Category:Guerrilla organizations]]\n[[Category:Military history of Cyprus]]\n[[Category:National liberation movements]]\n[[Category:Secession in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Separatism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:EOKA|*]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Cyprus\u2013Greece relations]]\n[[Category:Greek revolutionary organizations]]\n[[Category:Megali Idea]]\n[[Category:Anti-English sentiment]]\n", "name_user": "Rafael Mich", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EOKA"}
{"title_page": "Think About Things", "text_new": "{{About|the song also known as \"Gagnamagni\u00f0\"|the band itself|Gagnamagni\u00f0}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Think About Things\n| cover      = \n| type       = single\n| format     = \n| artist     = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] & [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]]\n| released   = 10 January 2020\n| genre      = \n| length     = \n| label      = \n| writer     = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson]]\n| chronology = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] singles\n| prev_title = \u00c9g Er A\u00f0 F\u00edla Mig (Langar Ekki A\u00f0 Hv\u00edla Mig)\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = \n{{Infobox song contest entry|embed=yes\n| song        = {{flagicon|Iceland}} \"Think About Things\"\n| year        = 2020\n| country     = Iceland\n| artist      = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] & [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]]\n| language    = English \n| composer    = Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson\n| lyricist    = Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson\n| place       =\n| place_semi  = ''Contest cancelled''\n| points_semi = \n| prev        = Hatri\u00f0 mun sigra\n| prev_link   = Hatri\u00f0 mun sigra\n| next        =\n| next_link   =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Think About Things'''\" is a song by [[Iceland|Icelandic]] singer [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson]] and his band [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]]. The song was released on 10 January 2020 with the [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]] title \"'''Gagnamagni\u00f0'''\" ({{lit|\"The datavolume\"|lk=yes}}), the name of the band. It was chosen to represent [[Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] in [[Rotterdam]], [[The Netherlands]] on 29 February 2020.<ref>[https://escxtra.com/2020/02/29/dadi-iceland-rotterdam Iceland decided for Rotterdam] retrieved 29 February 2020</ref> The band were going to compete in Eurovision with the English version of their song.<ref name=\"escbubble interview\">{{Cite web|url=https://escbubble.com/2020/02/dadi-freyr-i-originally-wrote-the-song-in-english-to-me-that-is-the-real-version-of-the-song/|title=Da\u00f0i Freyr: \u201cI originally wrote the song in English to me that is the real version of the song\u201d|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background and composition ==\nThe song has two different-language versions \u2013 one in Icelandic (\"Gagnamagni\u00f0\"; released 10 January 2020) and one in English (\"Think About Things\"). The meanings of the two versions' lyrics differ. In an interview, Da\u00f0i stated that the Icelandic version's lyrics \"talk about [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]] (the fictional band we perform as in [[S\u00f6ngvakeppnin]]) coming from the future and outer space to save the world with their brand new dance\".\n\nThe band would have competed in Eurovision with the English version of their song. Da\u00f0i has stated that he considers the English-language lyrics to be \"the real version of the song\". Da\u00f0i has described how the English lyrics of the song are about his infant daughter:<ref name=\"escbubble interview\"/>\n\n{{Quote|The lyrics in Think About Things are some of the most personal I have written. The song is about my little girl who was born in April of last year. I am talking about the feeling you get in the first few days and weeks where you know that you love this person with all your heart even though you don\u2019t really get that much interaction. In the start she doesn\u2019t do so much, so I am very excited to know what she thinks about all kinds of things. Now she is almost 10 months and has become such a character so the lyrics don\u2019t really apply as much anymore, she is starting to let us know what she is thinking.}}\n\n==Eurovision Song Contest==\n{{Main|Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\nThe song was scheduled to represent [[Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]], after [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] & [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]] was selected through ''[[S\u00f6ngvakeppnin 2020]]'', the music competition that selects Iceland's entries for the Eurovision Song Contest. On 28 January 2020, a special allocation draw was held which placed each country into one of the two semi-finals, as well as which half of the show they would perform in. Iceland was placed into the second semi-final, to be held on 14 May 2020, and was scheduled to perform in the first half of the show.\n\n== Music video ==\nThe song's music video (in English) was released on 14 February 2020.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VFZNvj-HfBU</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|3|artist=Da\u00f0i og Gagnamagni\u00f0|song=Think About Things|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Iceland ([[Music of Iceland|Tonlist]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://plotutidindi.is/lagalistinn/|title=T\u00d3NLISTINN \u2013 L\u00d6G|language=Icelandic|publisher=[[Music of Iceland|Tonlist]]|accessdate=25 March 2020|archiveurl=http://archive.is/bLpVV|archivedate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 94\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|66|date=20200306|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKdownload|62|date=20200320|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 March 2020}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2020]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Iceland]]\n[[Category:Songs about children]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the song also known as \"Gagnamagni\u00f0\"|the band itself|Gagnamagni\u00f0}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Think About Things\n| cover      = \n| type       = single\n| format     = \n| artist     = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] & [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]]\n| released   = 10 January 2020\n| genre      = \n| length     = \n| label      = \n| writer     = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson]]\n| chronology = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] singles\n| prev_title = \u00c9g Er A\u00f0 F\u00edla Mig (Langar Ekki A\u00f0 Hv\u00edla Mig)\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = \n{{Infobox song contest entry|embed=yes\n| song        = {{flagicon|Iceland}} \"Think About Things\"\n| year        = 2020\n| country     = Iceland\n| artist      = [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] & [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]]\n| language    = English \n| composer    = Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson\n| lyricist    = Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson\n| place       =\n| place_semi  = ''Contest cancelled''\n| points_semi = \n| prev        = Hatri\u00f0 mun sigra\n| prev_link   = Hatri\u00f0 mun sigra\n| next        =\n| next_link   =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Think About Things'''\" is a song by [[Iceland|Icelandic]] singer [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson]] and his band [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]]. The song was released on 10 January 2020 with the [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]] title \"'''Gagnamagni\u00f0'''\" ({{lit|\"The datavolume\"|lk=yes}}), the name of the band. It was chosen to represent [[Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] in [[Rotterdam]], [[The Netherlands]] on 29 February 2020.<ref>[https://escxtra.com/2020/02/29/dadi-iceland-rotterdam Iceland decided for Rotterdam] retrieved 29 February 2020</ref> The band were going to compete in Eurovision with the English version of their song.<ref name=\"escbubble interview\">{{Cite web|url=https://escbubble.com/2020/02/dadi-freyr-i-originally-wrote-the-song-in-english-to-me-that-is-the-real-version-of-the-song/|title=Da\u00f0i Freyr: \u201cI originally wrote the song in English to me that is the real version of the song\u201d|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background and composition ==\nThe song has two different-language versions \u2013 one in Icelandic (\"Gagnamagni\u00f0\"; released 10 January 2020) and one in English (\"Think About Things\"). The meanings of the two versions' lyrics differ. In an interview, Da\u00f0i stated that the Icelandic version's lyrics \"talk about [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]] (the fictional band we perform as in [[S\u00f6ngvakeppnin]]) coming from the future and outer space to save the world with their brand new dance\".\n\nThe band would have competed in Eurovision with the English version of their song. Da\u00f0i has stated that he considers the English-language lyrics to be \"the real version of the song\". Da\u00f0i has described how the English lyrics of the song are about his infant daughter:<ref name=\"escbubble interview\"/>\n\n{{Quote|The lyrics in Think About Things are some of the most personal I have written. The song is about my little girl who was born in April of last year. I am talking about the feeling you get in the first few days and weeks where you know that you love this person with all your heart even though you don\u2019t really get that much interaction. In the start she doesn\u2019t do so much, so I am very excited to know what she thinks about all kinds of things. Now she is almost 10 months and has become such a character so the lyrics don\u2019t really apply as much anymore, she is starting to let us know what she is thinking.}}\n\n==Eurovision Song Contest==\n{{Main|Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\nThe song was scheduled to represent [[Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]], after [[Da\u00f0i Freyr P\u00e9tursson|Da\u00f0i]] & [[Gagnamagni\u00f0]] was selected through ''[[S\u00f6ngvakeppnin 2020]]'', the music competition that selects Iceland's entries for the Eurovision Song Contest. On 28 January 2020, a special allocation draw was held which placed each country into one of the two semi-finals, as well as which half of the show they would perform in. Iceland was placed into the second semi-final, to be held on 14 May 2020, and was scheduled to perform in the first half of the show.\n\n== Music video ==\nThe song's music video (in English) was released on 14 February 2020.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VFZNvj-HfBU</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|6|artist=Da\u00f0i og Gagnamagni\u00f0|song=Think About Things|rowheader=true|accessdate=28 March 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Iceland ([[Music of Iceland|Tonlist]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://plotutidindi.is/lagalistinn/|title=T\u00d3NLISTINN \u2013 L\u00d6G|language=Icelandic|publisher=[[Music of Iceland|Tonlist]]|accessdate=25 March 2020|archiveurl=http://archive.is/bLpVV|archivedate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 94\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|66|date=20200306|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKdownload|62|date=20200320|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 March 2020}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2020]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Iceland]]\n[[Category:Songs about children]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Think_About_Things"}
{"title_page": "Roman Brother", "text_new": "{{Short description|American-bred Thoroughbred racehorse}}\n\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Roman Brother\n| image = \n| caption = \n| sire = Third Brother\n| grandsire = [[Princequillo]]\n| dam = Roman Zephyr\n| damsire = Roman\n| sex = [[Gelding]]\n| foaled = May 27, 1961\n| country =  United States\n| colour = [[Bay (horse)|Bay]]\n| breeder = [[Ocala Stud Farm]]\n| owner = [[Louis Wolfson|Harbor View Farm]]\n| trainer = [[Burley Parke]]\n| record = 42: 16-10-5\n| earnings = $943,473\n| race = [[Champagne Stakes (United States)|Champagne Stakes]] (1963)<br/>[[Bahamas Stakes]] (1964)<br/>[[Everglades Stakes]] (1964)<br/>[[Jersey Derby]] (1964)<br/>[[American Derby]] (1964)<br/>[[Discovery Handicap]] (1964)<br/>[[Jockey Club Gold Cup]] (1965)<br/>[[Woodward Stakes]] (1965)<br/>[[Manhattan Handicap]] (1965)\n|awards = [[American Champion Older Male Horse]] (1965)<br/>[[American Horse of the Year|DRF American Horse of the Year]] (1965)\n|honours =  \n|updated= \n }}\n'''Roman Brother''' (May 27, 1961 \u2013 March 8, 1991) was an  American [[Eclipse Award|Champion]] [[Thoroughbred]] [[horse racing|racehorse]]. As a two-year-old, he was initially overshadowed by his stable companion [[Raise a Native]] before emerging as one of the year's leading juveniles with a win in the [[Champagne Stakes (United States)|Champagne Stakes]]. As a three-year-old, he was highly tried, running twenty times and winning six races including the [[Jersey Derby]] and the [[American Derby]]. He was also placed second in the [[Belmont Stakes]] and the [[Jockey Club Gold Cup]]. He reached his peak as a four-year-old in 1965 when he was voted [[American Horse of the Year]] in a poll conducted by the ''[[Daily Racing Form]]''.\n\n==Background==\nRoman Brother was a bay gelding bred by the [[Ocala]] Stud Farm in [[Marion County, Florida|Marion County]] [[Florida]]. He was sired by Third Brother, who won the [[Long Island Handicap]] for his owner-breeder [[Christopher Chenery]] in 1956. Third Brother showed some promise as a stallion before his death in 1963: in addition to Roman Brother, he sired Exceedingly, who defeated [[Damascus]] in the William Dupont Jr. Handicap. Roman Brother's dam, Roman Zephyr, won four races and was a descendant of the influential broodmare [[Plucky Liege]]. In January 1963, Roman Brother was sent to the Florida Breeders' sale, where he sold for $23,500 (the second highest price at the sale) to Farnsworth Farm.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ivwjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EwUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4030,5612602&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Ocala horse brings record price at Florida Breeders' sale |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner |date=January 29, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\nHe entered into the ownership of [[Louis Wolfson|Louis Wolfson's]] Harbor View Farm and was trained by future [[National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Burley Parke]]. Roman Brother was an unusually small Thoroughbred, standing 15.1 [[Hand (unit)|hands]] high<ref name=\"google7374\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-OFUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XzwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=7374,1909236&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother |publisher=Leader-Post |date=November 9, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> and weighing in at 889 pounds just before the Belmont Stakes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rCoNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iGwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5439,1014889&dq=jimmy+conway |title=Quadrangle impressive in final Belmont prep |publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=June 5, 1964 |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> Contemporary newspapers nicknamed him the \"Mighty Mite\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qhcrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D50FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4128,2812716&dq=roman-brother+mighty-mite&hl=en |title=Quadrangle upset winner in Belmont |publisher=Reading Eagle |date=June 7, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref><ref name=\"google4440\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gy5JAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2YMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4440,5158586&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother breezes to 5-length victory |publisher=Youngstown Vindicator |date=October 31, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=95haAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h0sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4042,5602938&dq=roman-brother+mighty-mite&hl=en |title=Roman Brother moves to title |publisher=Ellensburg Daily Record |date=November 8, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Mighty Mites set in Flamingo race\"/> Roman Brother was described by one of his handlers as \"all heart\" but also \"a mean little devil\".<ref name=\"google7374\"/>\n\n==Racing career==\n\n===1963: two-year-old season===\nIn the summer of 1963, the leading two-year-old in Parke's stable was Raise a Native, who was undefeated in four races and was regarded as the best horse of his generation before his career was ended by injury in early August.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TJ4yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t-kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2537,482495&dq=raise-a-native&hl=en |title=Nation's top colt injured |publisher=Miami News |date=August 2, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> At the time of Raise a Native's injury, his stable companion, Roman Brother, who had been [[gelded]] before the start of his racing career, had appeared only once on the racecourse, winning a maiden race at [[Aqueduct Racetrack]] on July 25.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lives, the Times and the Past Performances of America's Greatest Thoroughbreds |author=Daily Racing Form Staff |publisher=DRF Press |year=2011}}</ref> The gelding made steady progress before emerging as a top-class horse in autumn. Racing at Aqueduct, Roman Brother won two allowance races before challenging for the [[Champagne Stakes (United States)|Champagne Stakes]] on October 13. Wolfson paid a supplementary fee of $10,000 to run Roman Brother, as he had not been among the original entries<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9A0fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_JoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5372,1925886&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother takes rich $152,150 purse |publisher=Tuscaloosa News |date=October 13, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> for the race, which carried prize money of $212,150, making it the most valuable race ever run in New York. Ridden by [[John L. Rotz]], Roman Brother tracked the leaders before taking the lead early in the straight and drawing away from his ten opponents to win by four and a half lengths.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-X0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wukFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5946,4562351&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother wins Champagne Stakes |publisher=Miami News |date=October 13, 1961 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> His win was marked at Ocala Stud Farm by the ringing of the old ship's bell which was used to mark major successes by the stud's produce.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oE9SAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3XwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4277,1255999&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Ship's bell rings for Roman Brother |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 13, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\nDespite losing his undefeated record when second to [[Hurry to Market]] at [[Garden State Park]], Roman Brother started favorite for the [[Garden State Futurity]] at the same track on November 9.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sFoyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6ekFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2190,2869282&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother tops Garden State Stakes |publisher=Miami News |date=November 8, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> In a race which carried world record prize money of $317,390, he finished second, beaten a length by Hurry to Market. An objection by Rotz against the winner for causing interference was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HJtFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=d7wMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3663,1253724&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Hurry to Market survives foul; wins big purse |publisher=Telegraph-Herald |date=November 10, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Raise a Native and Hurry to Market topped the polls for the title of [[American Champion Two-Year-Old Colt]], Roman Brother was reported to be the biggest money winner of his generation in 1963.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=en4yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3-kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2314,4385994&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Going, going gone: another Florida winner |publisher=Miami News |date=January 26, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref>\n\n===1964: three-year-old season===\nRoman Brother began his season in his native Florida. After finishing third on his debut, he won the seven-furlong [[Bahamas Stakes]] over seven [[furlong]]s at [[Hialeah Park]], surviving a rough race to win in a time of 1:23.2. By this time, he was regarded as a leading contender for the [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing#United States Triple Crowns|U.S. Triple Crown]] series.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VHEhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Q4gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3701,790684&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother wins Hialeah Bahamas stake |publisher=Schenectady Gazette |date=February 6, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> Later in February, Roman Brother moved up to nine furlongs for the [[Everglades Stakes]], in which he started favorite. Ridden by [[Manuel Ycaza]], the gelding came from well off the pace to catch Mr. Brick in the closing strides and win by a head. After the race, Ycaza described the winner as \"an awful willing little horse\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=M2kyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=H7cFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1021,4863715&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother captures feature |publisher=Palm Beach Post |date=February 20, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref>  In the [[Flamingo Stakes]] on March 3, Roman Brother was matched against [[Northern Dancer]], another unusually small thoroughbred, in what was described in the press as a meeting of the \"Mighty Mites\".<ref name=\"Mighty Mites set in Flamingo race\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=K_otAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FpcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7015,131342&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Mighty Mites set in Flamingo race |publisher=Palm Beach Daily News |date=March 1, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> Northern Dancer won, with Roman Brother fifth in a [[Tie (draw)|dead-heat]] with Dandy K, beaten more than fifteen lengths by the winner. Three weeks later, Roman Brother failed to concede ten [[Pound (mass)|pounds]] to Dandy K when finishing second in the [[Fountain of Youth Stakes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=23tPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CgUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3189,5560110&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother finishes 2nd |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner |date=March 26, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> On the final start of his Florida campaign, Roman Brother again finished fifth behind Northern Dancer, this time in the [[Florida Derby]].\n\nIn April, Roman Brother moved north and finished third to Mr Brick and [[Quadrangle (horse)|Quadrangle]] in the [[Wood Memorial Stakes]] at [[Aqueduct Racetrack]]. He was then sent to [[Churchill Downs]] where he prepared for the Derby by running second to the Californian colt [[Hill Rise]] in the [[Derby Trial Stakes]]. Four days later, Roman Brother was drawn on the outside of the twelve-runner field for the Kentucky Derby, for which Hill Rise was made favorite ahead of Northern Dancer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=S59FAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gbwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4510,8020955&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Twelve nominated for Derby |publisher=Telegraph-Herald |date=April 29, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> Roman Brother was beaten four lengths in fourth place behind Northern Dancer, Hill Rise and The Scoundrel. After finishing fifth in the [[Preakness Stakes]], he broke a run of seven defeats by winning the $125,300 [[Jersey Derby]] at Garden State Park. Parke only ran the gelding because The Scoundrel had been injured, but Roman Brother took the lead on the turn into the stretch and drew clear to beat Mr. Brick by three lengths.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fLBTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1TgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1496,5424192&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother wins rich Jersey Derby |publisher=St. Joseph News-Press |date=May 31, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> A week later, he ran second to Quadrangle in the [[Belmont Stakes]], finishing ahead of Northern Dancer and Hill Rise.\n\nAt the end of June, Roman Brother was sent to [[Arlington Park]], where he ran second to Dandy K when odds-on favorite for the $100,000 [[Chicagoan Handicap]]. Two weeks later, he finished third to Quadrangle in the [[Dwyer Stakes]] at Aqueduct. In August, Roman Brother ran fourth behind the filly [[Tosmah]] in the [[Arlington Classic]] and then contested the [[American Derby]] at the same track three weeks later. Starting the 2/1 favorite, he produced a strong finish to win the $134,300 prize by a length from Lt. Stevens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/08/30/archives/favored-roman-brother-mallies-to-take-134300-american-derby-by.html |title=Favored Roman Brother Rallies to Take $134,300 |publisher=New York Times |date=2012-06-10 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Roman Brother's next target was the inaugural running of the $144,820 New Hampshire Sweepstake at [[Rockingham Park]]. Ridden by [[Fernando Alvarez (jockey)|Fernando Alvarez]], he came from last place in the backstretch to win by half a length from Knightly Manner in a track record time of 1:55.8. It was the gelding's fifth win in seventeen runs since the start of the year and took his career earnings to $627,008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XjJgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yW8NAAAAIBAJ&pg=5471,1723149&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Sweepstakes Prize to Roman Brother |publisher=Saskatoon Star-Phoenix |date=September 14, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Two weeks later, he defeated Lt. Stevens by a nose in the [[Discovery Handicap]] at Aqueduct.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nichols |first=Joe |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/09/29/archives/roman-brother-victor-here-harbor-view-colt-scores-by-a-nose-beats.html |title=Roman Brother Victor Here |publisher=New York Times |date=1964-09-29 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn October, Roman Brother was moved up in distance for another meeting with Quadrangle in the [[Lawrence Realization Stakes]] over one and five-eighth miles at Aqueduct. He failed by a nose to catch Quadrangle but was blocked on three occasions and was given a \"poorly judged\" ride by Alvarez.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SzlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=regDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2470,4720326&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Quadrangle is winner |publisher=Spokesman-Review |date=October 14, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Roman Brother and Quadrangle met again in the two-mile [[Jockey Club Gold Cup]] on October 31, but most interest was attracted by [[Kelso (horse)|Kelso]], who was attempting to win the race for a fifth time and to become the biggest money winner in racing history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=StIhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v54FAAAAIBAJ&pg=3852,6527421&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Kelso aims for money mark today |publisher=Daytona Beach Morning Journal |date=October 31, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Kelso won easily, and Roman Brother beat Quadrangle by six lengths for second place.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YRdZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8ugDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4841,398389&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Kelso wins Jockey Club Gold Cup |publisher=Spokesman-Review |date=November 1, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>\n\n===1965: four-year-old season===\nFor the start of his 1965 campaign, Roman Brother was sent to compete in [[California]]. He finished last of the ten runners in the Malibu Stakes at [[Santa Anita Park]] on January 2 and ninth behind Hill Rise in the [[San Fernando Stakes]] two weeks later. A move to Florida in February brought little improvement as he finished seventh to Sunstruck in the [[Seminole Handicap]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6JwyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OekFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4700,2413696&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Hurry to Market's return to action |publisher=Miami News |date=February 8, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref>\n\nAfter a five-month break, Roman Brother, ridden by his new regular jockey [[Braulio Baeza]], returned in July to win an allowance race at Aqueduct and then ran second to [[Pia Star]] in the [[Brooklyn Handicap]], with Kelso in third. He won a minor race at [[Saratoga Race Course|Saratoga]] before finishing ahead of Kelso again in the Aqueduct Stakes in September, when the geldings finished third and fourth behind [[Malicious (1961 horse)|Malicious]]. Roman Brother then finished second to the mare [[Old Hat (horse)|Old Hat]] in the [[Michigan Mile And One-Eighth Handicap]].\n\nWith Kelso ruled out for the season with an eye injury<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAsrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2335,441854&dq=woodward-stakes&hl=en |title=Old Eye injury sidelines Kelso |publisher=Reading Eagle |date=October 2, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> Roman Brother dominated the rest of America's older horses in October, winning all three of his races. On October 2, he won the [[Woodward Stakes]] from Royal Gunner, with Malicious taking third. Ten days later, Roman Brother won the [[Manhattan Handicap]] by eight lengths from Hill Rise. According to the [[New York Times]], the manner of his victory \"left little doubt of his superiority\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Nichols |first=Joe |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/10/13/archives/roman-brother-scores-8length-victory-in-56000-manhattan-aqueduct.html |title=Roman Brother Scores 8-Length Victory in $56,000 Manhattan |publisher=New York Times |date=1965-10-13 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> over the rest of the handicap division. On October 30 at Aqueduct, Roman Brother appeared for a second attempt at the Jockey Club Gold Cup. Taking the lead on the final turn, he drew away from his rivals to win by five lengths from Berenjenal. According to the [[Associated Press]] reporter, Baeza \"never had an easier ride\".<ref name=\"google4440\"/>\n\nOn his final race of the season, Roman Brother moved onto turf and was made favorite for the [[Washington, D.C. International Stakes]] at [[Laurel Park Racecourse]].<ref name=\"google7374\"/> He was among the leaders from the start and finished third behind the French-trained runners [[Diatome (horse)|Diatome]] and [[Carvin (horse)|Carvin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aPhRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VnQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6956,1112787&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=French horses one-two |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |date=November 12, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref>\n\nRoman Brother was named 1965 [[American Horse of the Year|Horse of The Year]] after topping a poll organised by the publishers of ''[[Daily Racing Form]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ws1NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tg4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3700,2712842&dq=roman-brother+horse-of-the-year&hl=en |title=Roman Brother:Horse of the Year |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner  |date= |accessdate=2012-02-27}}</ref> becoming the first horse sold at public auction to be so honored.<ref name=\"million\"/> The two-year-old filly [[Moccasin (horse)|Moccasin]] won the two rival polls organized by the Thoroughbred Racing Association<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_vZbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=S1QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2712,902052&dq=moccasin+horse-of-the-year&hl=en |title=Filly Takes Horse of the Year |publisher=Youngstown Vindicator |date=1965-12-03 |accessdate=2012-02-27}}</ref> and ''Turf and Sports Digest'', beating Roman Brother by 44 votes to 39 in the latter poll.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8GAyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4rIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4246,1405708&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Moccasin choice as top horse |publisher=Beaver County Times |date=December 7, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> Roman Brother was named [[American Champion Older Male Horse|Champion Handicap horse]] in all three polls.\n\n===1966: five-year-old season===\nRoman Brother opened his five-year-old season by winning a seven-furlong race at Hialeah on January 25. The prize took his career earnings to $940,403, leading to speculation that he was poised to become the next equine millionaire.<ref name=\"million\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7nVPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5630,6132156&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother sweeps into million range |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner |date=January 26, 1966 |accessdate=2012-07-15}}</ref> On February 5, Roman Brother, carrying 126 pounds, started 1/2 favorite for the Seminole Handicap at the same track. The gelding was never in contention, finishing fourth to Convex.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=e9YzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=c-sFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1452,1548377&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=It's Convex surprise winner in Seminole |publisher=Miami News |date=February 6, 1966 |accessdate=2012-07-15}}</ref> Roman Brother sustained an injury to his left ankle in the race, which forced him to miss an intended run in the [[Widener Handicap]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/02/09/archives/roman-brother-injured-and-will-miss-widener.html|title=Roman Brother Injured And Will Miss Widener|accessdate=2012-07-16|date=February 8, 1966|publisher=New York Times}}</ref> The injury did not respond to treatment, and Roman Brother was retired from racing.\n\n==Retirement and Death==\nRoman Brother spent his retirement at Harbor View Farm before being moved to Stephen and Gary Wolfson's Happy Valley Farm after the sale of Harbor View. On the afternoon of March 8, 1991, he died after a severe bout with colic, less than three months before his 30th birthday. His rival Northern Dancer, who like Roman Brother was foaled on May 27, 1961, had been euthanized exactly 16 weeks earlier on November 16, 1990, due to complications also from colic. The two had been one of the only known close rivals ever to have the same foaling date and to die within four months of each other due to the same illness.\n\nThe Roman Brother Handicap, a race restricted to Florida-breds and run at Hialeah, was named in the gelding's honor.\n\n==Pedigree==\n\n{{Pedigree \n| name = Roman Brother (USA) bay gelding 1961<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.equineline.com/Free-5X-Pedigree.cfm?page_state=ORDER_AND_CONFIRM&reference_number=421621&registry=T&horse_name=Roman%20Brother&dam_name=Roman%20Zephyr&foaling_year=1961&nicking_stats_indicator=Y |title=Roman Brother pedigree |publisher=equineline.com |date=2012-05-08 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n| f = Third Brother (USA)<br />1953\n| m = Roman Zephyr (USA)<br />1947\n| ff = [[Princequillo]] (USA)<br />1940\n| fm = Hildene (USA)<br />1938\n| mf = [[Roman (horse)|Roman]] (USA)<br />1937\n| mm = Blois (USA) <br />1940\n| fff = [[Prince Rose]]\n| ffm = Cosquilla\n| fmf = [[Bubbling Over (horse)|Bubbling Over]]\n| fmm = Fancy Racket\n| mff = [[Sir Gallahad III|Sir Gallahad]]\n| mfm = Buckup\n| mmf = [[Man o' War]]\n| mmm = Mademoiselle de Valo\n| ffff = [[Rose Prince (horse)|Rose Prince]]\n| fffm = Indolence\n| ffmf = [[Papyrus (horse)|Papyrus]]\n| ffmm = Quick Thought\n| fmff = North Star\n| fmfm = Beaming Beauty\n| fmmf = Wrack\n| fmmm = Ultimate Fancy\n| mfff = [[Teddy (horse)|Teddy]]\n| mffm = [[Plucky Liege]]\n| mfmf = [[Buchan (horse)|Buchan]]\n| mfmm = Look Up\n| mmff = [[Fair Play (horse)|Fair Play]]\n| mmfm = Mahubah\n| mmmf = [[Sardanapale (horse)|Sardanapale]]\n| mmmm = Marguerite de Valois (Family: 16-a)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodlines.net/TB/Families/Family16a.htm |title=Miss Agnes - Family 16-a |publisher=Bloodlines.net |date= |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n|}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:1961 racehorse births]]\n[[Category:1991 racehorse deaths]]\n[[Category:Thoroughbred family 16-a]]\n[[Category:Racehorses bred in Florida]]\n[[Category:Racehorses trained in the United States]]\n[[Category:American Thoroughbred Horse of the Year]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American-bred Thoroughbred racehorse}}\n\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Roman Brother\n| image = \n| caption = \n| sire = Third Brother\n| grandsire = [[Princequillo]]\n| dam = Roman Zephyr\n| damsire = Roman\n| sex = [[Gelding]]\n| foaled = May 27, 1961\n| country =  United States\n| colour = [[Bay (horse)|Bay]]\n| breeder = [[Ocala Stud Farm]]\n| owner = [[Louis Wolfson|Harbor View Farm]]\n| trainer = [[Burley Parke]]\n| record = 42: 16-10-5\n| earnings = $943,473\n| race = [[Champagne Stakes (United States)|Champagne Stakes]] (1963)<br/>[[Bahamas Stakes]] (1964)<br/>[[Everglades Stakes]] (1964)<br/>[[Jersey Derby]] (1964)<br/>[[American Derby]] (1964)<br/>[[Discovery Handicap]] (1964)<br/>[[Jockey Club Gold Cup]] (1965)<br/>[[Woodward Stakes]] (1965)<br/>[[Manhattan Handicap]] (1965)\n|awards = [[American Champion Older Male Horse]] (1965)<br/>[[American Horse of the Year|DRF American Horse of the Year]] (1965)\n|honours =  \n|updated= \n }}\n'''Roman Brother''' (May 27, 1961 \u2013 March 8, 1991) was an  American [[Eclipse Award|Champion]] [[Thoroughbred]] [[horse racing|racehorse]]. As a two-year-old, he was initially overshadowed by his stable companion [[Raise a Native]] before emerging as one of the year's leading juveniles with a win in the [[Champagne Stakes (United States)|Champagne Stakes]]. As a three-year-old, he was highly tried, running twenty times and winning six races including the [[Jersey Derby]] and the [[American Derby]]. He was also placed second in the [[Belmont Stakes]] and the [[Jockey Club Gold Cup]]. He reached his peak as a four-year-old in 1965 when he was voted [[American Horse of the Year]] in a poll conducted by the ''[[Daily Racing Form]]''.\n\n==Background==\nRoman Brother was a bay gelding bred by the [[Ocala]] Stud Farm in [[Marion County, Florida|Marion County]] [[Florida]]. He was sired by Third Brother, who won the [[Long Island Handicap]] for his owner-breeder [[Christopher Chenery]] in 1956. Third Brother showed some promise as a stallion before his death in 1963: in addition to Roman Brother, he sired Exceedingly, who defeated [[Damascus]] in the William Dupont Jr. Handicap. Roman Brother's dam, Roman Zephyr, won four races and was a descendant of the influential broodmare [[Plucky Liege]]. In January 1963, Roman Brother was sent to the Florida Breeders' sale, where he sold for $23,500 (the second highest price at the sale) to Farnsworth Farm.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ivwjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EwUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4030,5612602&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Ocala horse brings record price at Florida Breeders' sale |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner |date=January 29, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\nHe entered into the ownership of [[Louis Wolfson|Louis Wolfson's]] Harbor View Farm and was trained by future [[National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Burley Parke]]. Roman Brother was an unusually small Thoroughbred, standing 15.1 [[Hand (unit)|hands]] high<ref name=\"google7374\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-OFUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XzwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=7374,1909236&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother |publisher=Leader-Post |date=November 9, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> and weighing in at 889 pounds just before the Belmont Stakes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rCoNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iGwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5439,1014889&dq=jimmy+conway |title=Quadrangle impressive in final Belmont prep |publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=June 5, 1964 |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> Contemporary newspapers nicknamed him the \"Mighty Mite\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qhcrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D50FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4128,2812716&dq=roman-brother+mighty-mite&hl=en |title=Quadrangle upset winner in Belmont |publisher=Reading Eagle |date=June 7, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref><ref name=\"google4440\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gy5JAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2YMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4440,5158586&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother breezes to 5-length victory |publisher=Youngstown Vindicator |date=October 31, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=95haAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h0sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4042,5602938&dq=roman-brother+mighty-mite&hl=en |title=Roman Brother moves to title |publisher=Ellensburg Daily Record |date=November 8, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Mighty Mites set in Flamingo race\"/> Roman Brother was described by one of his handlers as \"all heart\" but also \"a mean little devil\".<ref name=\"google7374\"/>\n\n==Racing career==\n\n===1963: two-year-old season===\nIn the summer of 1963, the leading two-year-old in Parke's stable was Raise a Native, who was undefeated in four races and was regarded as the best horse of his generation before his career was ended by injury in early August.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TJ4yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t-kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2537,482495&dq=raise-a-native&hl=en |title=Nation's top colt injured |publisher=Miami News |date=August 2, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> At the time of Raise a Native's injury, his stable companion, Roman Brother, who had been [[gelded]] before the start of his racing career, had appeared only once on the racecourse, winning a maiden race at [[Aqueduct Racetrack]] on July 25.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lives, the Times and the Past Performances of America's Greatest Thoroughbreds |author=Daily Racing Form Staff |publisher=DRF Press |year=2011}}</ref> The gelding made steady progress before emerging as a top-class horse in autumn. Racing at Aqueduct, Roman Brother won two allowance races before challenging for the [[Champagne Stakes (United States)|Champagne Stakes]] on October 13. Wolfson paid a supplementary fee of $10,000 to run Roman Brother, as he had not been among the original entries<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9A0fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_JoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5372,1925886&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother takes rich $152,150 purse |publisher=Tuscaloosa News |date=October 13, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> for the race, which carried prize money of $212,150, making it the most valuable race ever run in New York. Ridden by [[John L. Rotz]], Roman Brother tracked the leaders before taking the lead early in the straight and drawing away from his ten opponents to win by four and a half lengths.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-X0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wukFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5946,4562351&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother wins Champagne Stakes |publisher=Miami News |date=October 13, 1961 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> His win was marked at Ocala Stud Farm by the ringing of the old ship's bell which was used to mark major successes by the stud's produce.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oE9SAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3XwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4277,1255999&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Ship's bell rings for Roman Brother |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 13, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\nDespite losing his undefeated record when second to [[Hurry to Market]] at [[Garden State Park]], Roman Brother started favorite for the [[Garden State Futurity]] at the same track on November 9.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sFoyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6ekFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2190,2869282&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother tops Garden State Stakes |publisher=Miami News |date=November 8, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> In a race which carried world record prize money of $317,390, he finished second, beaten a length by Hurry to Market. An objection by Rotz against the winner for causing interference was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HJtFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=d7wMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3663,1253724&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Hurry to Market survives foul; wins big purse |publisher=Telegraph-Herald |date=November 10, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Raise a Native and Hurry to Market topped the polls for the title of [[American Champion Two-Year-Old Colt]], Roman Brother was reported to be the biggest money winner of his generation in 1963.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=en4yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3-kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2314,4385994&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Going, going gone: another Florida winner |publisher=Miami News |date=January 26, 1963 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref>\n\n===1964: three-year-old season===\nRoman Brother began his season in his native Florida. After finishing third on his debut, he won the seven-furlong [[Bahamas Stakes]] over seven [[furlong]]s at [[Hialeah Park]], surviving a rough race to win in a time of 1:23.2. By this time, he was regarded as a leading contender for the [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing#United States Triple Crowns|U.S. Triple Crown]] series.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VHEhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Q4gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3701,790684&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother wins Hialeah Bahamas stake |publisher=Schenectady Gazette |date=February 6, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> Later in February, Roman Brother moved up to nine furlongs for the [[Everglades Stakes]], in which he started favorite. Ridden by [[Manuel Ycaza]], the gelding came from well off the pace to catch Mr. Brick in the closing strides and win by a head. After the race, Ycaza described the winner as \"an awful willing little horse\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=M2kyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=H7cFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1021,4863715&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother captures feature |publisher=Palm Beach Post |date=February 20, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref>  In the [[Flamingo Stakes]] on March 3, Roman Brother was matched against [[Northern Dancer]], another unusually small thoroughbred, in what was described in the press as a meeting of the \"Mighty Mites\".<ref name=\"Mighty Mites set in Flamingo race\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=K_otAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FpcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7015,131342&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Mighty Mites set in Flamingo race |publisher=Palm Beach Daily News |date=March 1, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> Northern Dancer won, with Roman Brother fifth in a [[Tie (draw)|dead-heat]] with Dandy K, beaten more than fifteen lengths by the winner. Three weeks later, Roman Brother failed to concede ten [[Pound (mass)|pounds]] to Dandy K when finishing second in the [[Fountain of Youth Stakes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=23tPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CgUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3189,5560110&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother finishes 2nd |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner |date=March 26, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> On the final start of his Florida campaign, Roman Brother again finished fifth behind Northern Dancer, this time in the [[Florida Derby]].\n\nIn April, Roman Brother moved north and finished third to Mr Brick and [[Quadrangle (horse)|Quadrangle]] in the [[Wood Memorial Stakes]] at [[Aqueduct Racetrack]]. He was then sent to [[Churchill Downs]] where he prepared for the Derby by running second to the Californian colt [[Hill Rise]] in the [[Derby Trial Stakes]]. Four days later, Roman Brother was drawn on the outside of the twelve-runner field for the Kentucky Derby, for which Hill Rise was made favorite ahead of Northern Dancer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=S59FAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gbwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4510,8020955&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Twelve nominated for Derby |publisher=Telegraph-Herald |date=April 29, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> Roman Brother was beaten four lengths in fourth place behind Northern Dancer, Hill Rise and The Scoundrel. After finishing fifth in the [[Preakness Stakes]], he broke a run of seven defeats by winning the $125,300 [[Jersey Derby]] at Garden State Park. Parke only ran the gelding because The Scoundrel had been injured, but Roman Brother took the lead on the turn into the stretch and drew clear to beat Mr. Brick by three lengths.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fLBTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1TgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1496,5424192&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother wins rich Jersey Derby |publisher=St. Joseph News-Press |date=May 31, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> A week later, he ran second to Quadrangle in the [[Belmont Stakes]], finishing ahead of Northern Dancer and Hill Rise.\n\nAt the end of June, Roman Brother was sent to [[Arlington Park]], where he ran second to Dandy K when odds-on favorite for the $100,000 [[Chicagoan Handicap]]. Two weeks later, he finished third to Quadrangle in the [[Dwyer Stakes]] at Aqueduct. In August, Roman Brother ran fourth behind the filly [[Tosmah]] in the [[Arlington Classic]] and then contested the [[American Derby]] at the same track three weeks later. Starting the 2/1 favorite, he produced a strong finish to win the $134,300 prize by a length from Lt. Stevens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/08/30/archives/favored-roman-brother-mallies-to-take-134300-american-derby-by.html |title=Favored Roman Brother Rallies to Take $134,300 |publisher=New York Times |date=2012-06-10 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Roman Brother's next target was the inaugural running of the $144,820 New Hampshire Sweepstake at [[Rockingham Park]]. Ridden by [[Fernando Alvarez (jockey)|Fernando Alvarez]], he came from last place in the backstretch to win by half a length from Knightly Manner in a track record time of 1:55.8. It was the gelding's fifth win in seventeen runs since the start of the year and took his career earnings to $627,008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XjJgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yW8NAAAAIBAJ&pg=5471,1723149&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=Sweepstakes Prize to Roman Brother |publisher=Saskatoon Star-Phoenix |date=September 14, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Two weeks later, he defeated Lt. Stevens by a nose in the [[Discovery Handicap]] at Aqueduct.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nichols |first=Joe |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/09/29/archives/roman-brother-victor-here-harbor-view-colt-scores-by-a-nose-beats.html |title=Roman Brother Victor Here |publisher=New York Times |date=1964-09-29 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn October, Roman Brother was moved up in distance for another meeting with Quadrangle in the [[Lawrence Realization Stakes]] over one and five-eighth miles at Aqueduct. He failed by a nose to catch Quadrangle but was blocked on three occasions and was given a \"poorly judged\" ride by Alvarez.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SzlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=regDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2470,4720326&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Quadrangle is winner |publisher=Spokesman-Review |date=October 14, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Roman Brother and Quadrangle met again in the two-mile [[Jockey Club Gold Cup]] on October 31, but most interest was attracted by [[Kelso (horse)|Kelso]], who was attempting to win the race for a fifth time and to become the biggest money winner in racing history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=StIhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v54FAAAAIBAJ&pg=3852,6527421&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Kelso aims for money mark today |publisher=Daytona Beach Morning Journal |date=October 31, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Kelso won easily, and Roman Brother beat Quadrangle by six lengths for second place.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YRdZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8ugDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4841,398389&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Kelso wins Jockey Club Gold Cup |publisher=Spokesman-Review |date=November 1, 1964 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>\n\n===1965: four-year-old season===\nFor the start of his 1965 campaign, Roman Brother was sent to compete in [[California]]. He finished last of the ten runners in the Malibu Stakes at [[Santa Anita Park]] on January 2 and ninth behind Hill Rise in the [[San Fernando Stakes]] two weeks later. A move to Florida in February brought little improvement as he finished seventh to Sunstruck in the [[Seminole Handicap]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6JwyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OekFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4700,2413696&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Hurry to Market's return to action |publisher=Miami News |date=February 8, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref>\n\nAfter a five-month break, Roman Brother, ridden by his new regular jockey [[Braulio Baeza]], returned in July to win an allowance race at Aqueduct and then ran second to [[Pia Star]] in the [[Brooklyn Handicap]], with Kelso in third. He won a minor race at [[Saratoga Race Course|Saratoga]] before finishing ahead of Kelso again in the Aqueduct Stakes in September, when the geldings finished third and fourth behind [[Malicious (1961 horse)|Malicious]]. Roman Brother then finished second to the mare [[Old Hat (horse)|Old Hat]] in the [[Michigan Mile And One-Eighth Handicap]].\n\nWith Kelso ruled out for the season with an eye injury<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAsrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2335,441854&dq=woodward-stakes&hl=en |title=Old Eye injury sidelines Kelso |publisher=Reading Eagle |date=October 2, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> Roman Brother dominated the rest of America's older horses in October, winning all three of his races. On October 2, he won the [[Woodward Stakes]] from Royal Gunner, with Malicious taking third. Ten days later, Roman Brother won the [[Manhattan Handicap]] by eight lengths from Hill Rise. According to the [[New York Times]], the manner of his victory \"left little doubt of his superiority\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Nichols |first=Joe |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/10/13/archives/roman-brother-scores-8length-victory-in-56000-manhattan-aqueduct.html |title=Roman Brother Scores 8-Length Victory in $56,000 Manhattan |publisher=New York Times |date=1965-10-13 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> over the rest of the handicap division. On October 30 at Aqueduct, Roman Brother appeared for a second attempt at the Jockey Club Gold Cup. Taking the lead on the final turn, he drew away from his rivals to win by five lengths from Berenjenal. According to the [[Associated Press]] reporter, Baeza \"never had an easier ride\".<ref name=\"google4440\"/>\n\nOn his final race of the season, Roman Brother moved onto turf and was made favorite for the [[Washington, D.C. International Stakes]] at [[Laurel Park Racecourse]].<ref name=\"google7374\"/> He was among the leaders from the start and finished third behind the French-trained runners [[Diatome (horse)|Diatome]] and [[Carvin (horse)|Carvin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aPhRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VnQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6956,1112787&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=French horses one-two |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |date=November 12, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref>\n\nRoman Brother was named 1965 [[American Horse of the Year|Horse of The Year]] after topping a poll organised by the publishers of ''[[Daily Racing Form]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ws1NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tg4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3700,2712842&dq=roman-brother+horse-of-the-year&hl=en |title=Roman Brother:Horse of the Year |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner  |date= |accessdate=2012-02-27}}</ref> becoming the first horse sold at public auction to be so honored.<ref name=\"million\"/> The two-year-old filly [[Moccasin (horse)|Moccasin]] won the two rival polls organized by the Thoroughbred Racing Association<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_vZbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=S1QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2712,902052&dq=moccasin+horse-of-the-year&hl=en |title=Filly Takes Horse of the Year |publisher=Youngstown Vindicator |date=1965-12-03 |accessdate=2012-02-27}}</ref> and ''Turf and Sports Digest'', beating Roman Brother by 44 votes to 39 in the latter poll.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8GAyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4rIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4246,1405708&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Moccasin choice as top horse |publisher=Beaver County Times |date=December 7, 1965 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> Roman Brother was named [[American Champion Older Male Horse|Champion Handicap horse]] in all three polls.\n\n===1966: five-year-old season===\nRoman Brother opened his five-year-old season by winning a seven-furlong race at Hialeah on January 25. The prize took his career earnings to $940,403, leading to speculation that he was poised to become the next equine millionaire.<ref name=\"million\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7nVPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5630,6132156&dq=roman-brother&hl=en |title=Roman Brother sweeps into million range |publisher=Ocala Star-Banner |date=January 26, 1966 |accessdate=2012-07-15}}</ref> On February 5, Roman Brother, carrying 126 pounds, started 1/2 favorite for the Seminole Handicap at the same track. The gelding was never in contention, finishing fourth to Convex.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=e9YzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=c-sFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1452,1548377&dq=roman+brother&hl=en |title=It's Convex surprise winner in Seminole |publisher=Miami News |date=February 6, 1966 |accessdate=2012-07-15}}</ref> Roman Brother sustained an injury to his left ankle in the race, which forced him to miss an intended run in the [[Widener Handicap]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/02/09/archives/roman-brother-injured-and-will-miss-widener.html|title=Roman Brother Injured And Will Miss Widener|accessdate=2012-07-16|date=February 8, 1966|publisher=New York Times}}</ref> The injury did not respond to treatment, and Roman Brother was retired from racing.\n\n==Retirement and Death==\nRoman Brother spent his retirement at Harbor View Farm before being moved to Stephen and Gary Wolfson's Happy Valley Farm after the sale of Harbor View. On the afternoon of March 8, 1991, he died after a severe bout with colic, less than three months before his 30th birthday. His rival Northern Dancer, who like Roman Brother was foaled on May 27, 1961, had been euthanized exactly 16 weeks earlier on November 16, 1990 due to complications also from colic. The two had been one of the only known close rivals ever to have the same foaling date and to die within four months of each other due to the same illness.\n\nThe Roman Brother Handicap, a race restricted to Florida-breds and run at Hialeah, was named in the gelding's honor.\n\n==Pedigree==\n\n{{Pedigree \n| name = Roman Brother (USA) bay gelding 1961<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.equineline.com/Free-5X-Pedigree.cfm?page_state=ORDER_AND_CONFIRM&reference_number=421621&registry=T&horse_name=Roman%20Brother&dam_name=Roman%20Zephyr&foaling_year=1961&nicking_stats_indicator=Y |title=Roman Brother pedigree |publisher=equineline.com |date=2012-05-08 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n| f = Third Brother (USA)<br />1953\n| m = Roman Zephyr (USA)<br />1947\n| ff = [[Princequillo]] (USA)<br />1940\n| fm = Hildene (USA)<br />1938\n| mf = [[Roman (horse)|Roman]] (USA)<br />1937\n| mm = Blois (USA) <br />1940\n| fff = [[Prince Rose]]\n| ffm = Cosquilla\n| fmf = [[Bubbling Over (horse)|Bubbling Over]]\n| fmm = Fancy Racket\n| mff = [[Sir Gallahad III|Sir Gallahad]]\n| mfm = Buckup\n| mmf = [[Man o' War]]\n| mmm = Mademoiselle de Valo\n| ffff = [[Rose Prince (horse)|Rose Prince]]\n| fffm = Indolence\n| ffmf = [[Papyrus (horse)|Papyrus]]\n| ffmm = Quick Thought\n| fmff = North Star\n| fmfm = Beaming Beauty\n| fmmf = Wrack\n| fmmm = Ultimate Fancy\n| mfff = [[Teddy (horse)|Teddy]]\n| mffm = [[Plucky Liege]]\n| mfmf = [[Buchan (horse)|Buchan]]\n| mfmm = Look Up\n| mmff = [[Fair Play (horse)|Fair Play]]\n| mmfm = Mahubah\n| mmmf = [[Sardanapale (horse)|Sardanapale]]\n| mmmm = Marguerite de Valois (Family: 16-a)<ref>